	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EU banana imports in the first year of the tariff-only regime</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 April 2007
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> In 2006, the first year of the EU’s tariff-only regime for bananas EU imports increased by 12.3% to 4,185 million tonnes. Imports from ACP countries rose by 18.6%, with particularly strong increases from Jamaica and Ghana whose exports rose by 173% and 478% respectively. ‘Cameroon and Ivory Coast retained their position as the main ACP banana suppliers to the EU’, accounting for around 53% of ACP exports. The EU is virtually the sole outlet for bananas from these two ACP countries. ‘Fair trade’ bananas are becoming important to vulnerable ACP banana suppliers. Before a House of Commons select committee the development of the trade in ‘fair trade’ bananas was described by the prime minister of the Commonwealth of Dominica, Roosevelt Skerrit, as ‘critical to Dominica’s development’, ensuring that ‘the social stability of our country is maintained, that poor people, particularly in rural communities, can enjoy a better standard of living’. He argued that ‘fair trade’ bananas had ‘reversed a nearly catastrophic recession in his country’. Other ‘fair trade’ banana suppliers include Ghana, Ecuador and Costa Rica.</p><p> Exports of ‘dollar’ bananas grew by 10.7% in 2006. Ecuador remained the single largest supplier to the EU market but with exports declining by 3.6%. In contrast, Guatemala’s exports grew by a massive 811%, while Peru, Brazil, Venezuela, Panama, Colombia and Costa Rica increased exports by 95%, 50%, 16%, 10.2%, 6.7% and 37% respectively. Latin American suppliers now account for 70% of EU banana supplies.</p><p> The EU is now the single largest market for Costa Rican bananas. While this increase reflects in part a recovery from flood damage ‘the increase in export levels has gone beyond making up lost ground’, exports were fully 10% higher than the average for 2002-2004. This growth is driven by government investments and technological innovation, which means that Costs Rica now has the highest yields per hectare in the world. Meanwhile there are fears in Ecuador that preferences for African bananas are distorting investment flows and thereby threatening an end to Ecuador’s banana exports according to Ecuadorian producers’ representatives. </p><p> In 2006 the EU’s own banana output was down by 1% to 641,754 tonnes, just 13% of overall supplies. While in February 2007 Canary Island banana exports increased by 22% compared to the corresponding month in 2006, at the beginning of March it was announced that Canary Island producers were withholding up to 20% of their normal supplies so as to ‘prevent a further market saturation on the Iberian peninsular’.</p><p> Meanwhile the EU has blocked Ecuador’s first attempt to establish a WTO panel on the new banana regime, maintaining that the new regime is compliant with WTO demands. However, should Ecuador submit a second request the EU will be unable to block a WTO panel.</p>
		
		
